<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Offset Gravure" class="currentChild" href="Offset_Gravure">Offset Gravure</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A variety of <a title="Gravure" href="Gravure">gravure</a> printing in which the image is transferred from a <a title="Gravure Cylinder" href="Gravure_Cylinder">gravure cylinder</a> to a rubber-covered <a title="Transfer Roller" href="Transfer_Roller">transfer roller</a> and, ultimately, to the substrate. See <a title="Gravure: Offset Gravure" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/Gravure:_Offset_Gravure">Gravure: Offset Gravure</a>. Offset gravure is also known as <a title="Indirect Gravure" href="Indirect_Gravure">indirect gravure</a>, and offset gravure that is performed on a flexographic press is known as <a title="Flexo Gravure" href="Flexo_Gravure">flexo gravure</a>. 
</p>
